igh, although we are getting an error with <span class="abbreviation">CAN<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Controller Area Network"></template></span>. We also get a CommandSchedular loop overrun. The only thing that seems very high right now is robotPeriodic at 0.509123s. Below I pasted screenshots of our riolog.</p>
<p><div class="lightbox-wrapper"><a class="lightbox" href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/3X/c/d/cdebd76b02ec12600dec37fbb5fbd8e9d68683e8.png" data-download-href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/cdebd76b02ec12600dec37fbb5fbd8e9d68683e8" title="image"><img src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/3X/c/d/cdebd76b02ec12600dec37fbb5fbd8e9d68683e8.png" alt="image" data-base62-sha1="tnFavsIytC46yvRZKnKGtwYgUDm" width="690" height="301" data-dominant-color="2B2827"><div class="meta"><svg class="fa d-icon d-icon-far-image svg-icon" aria-hidden="true"><use href="#far-image"></use></svg><span class="filename">image</span><span class="informations">759×332 12.8 KB</span><svg class="fa d-icon d-icon-discourse-expand svg-icon" aria-hidden="true"><use href="#discourse-expand"></use></svg></div></a></div><br>
<div class="lightbox-wrapper"><a class="lightbox" href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/3X/d/f/dfc944fe38cfc3cca76fc6f108354cce7f2f7403.png" data-download-href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/dfc944fe38cfc3cca76fc6f108354cce7f2f7403" title="image"><img src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/3X/d/f/dfc944fe38cfc3cca76fc6f108354cce7f2f7403.png" alt="image" data-base62-sha1="vVHH163Ge3hm66yekFTJkEeXoS7" width="690" height="379" data-dominant-color="2C2C28"><div class="meta"><svg class="fa d-icon d-icon-far-image svg-icon" aria-hidden="true"><use href="#far-image"></use></svg><span class="filename">image</span><span class="informations">730×401 13.3 KB</span><svg class="fa d-icon d-icon-discourse-expand svg-icon" aria-hidden="true"><use href="#discourse-expand"></use></svg></div></a></div></p>","post_number":5,"post_type":1,"posts_count":14,"updated_at":"2024-02-05T14:28:09.717Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":2,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":5,"reads":83,"readers_count":82,"score":46.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":453000,"topic_slug":"input-delay-on-swerve-drive-when-adding-other-subsystems","display_username":"Victoria","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/3X/c/d/cdebd76b02ec12600dec37fbb5fbd8e9d68683e8.png","internal":true,"reflection":false,"clicks":0},{"url":"https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/3X/d/f/dfc944fe38cfc3cca76fc6f108354cce7f2f7403.png","internal":true,"reflection":false,"clicks":0}],"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":12397,"username":"techplex","name":"Blake Bourque","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/techplex/{size}/195570_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":55902,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/input-delay-on-swerve-drive-when-adding-other-subsystems/453000/5","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3302138,"name":"Dylan Powers","username":"Dylan1259","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/dylan1259/{size}/161876_2.png","created_at":"2024-02-05T15:11:00.274Z","cooked":"<p>I took a look at your code and I noticed some things that could be slowing down your execute loops. Specifically in the <code>setMotors()</code> method of <code>AngleSubsystem.java</code>.</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">// motors going opposite directions, change to false if they need to go the same direction for any reason
followerMotor.setControl(new Follower(masterMotor.getDeviceID(), true));
set the mode to brake. make motor hard stop
masterMotor.setNeutralMode(NeutralModeValue.Brake);
followerMotor.setNeutralMode(NeutralModeValue.Brake);
</code></pre>
<p>All three of these lines seem like configuration statements that should be done once upon robot initialization. I have not used <code>TalonFX.setControl(Follower)</code> before but I THINK that you don’t need to repeatedly set that. Or at least there is a way to specify one motor as a follower of another once upon initialization. I do know that the <code>.setNeutralMode()</code> can be done upon initialization once and it will still work as intended.</p>
<p>Many configuration statements are not meant to be called periodically as they send a message over the <span class="abbreviation">CAN<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Controller Area Network"></template></span> bus, then block until they get a response they can return. That being said, it <em>shouldn’t</em> cause multiple seconds of input delay. If you are still having a problem tonight, post that here with any further data you can gather and I can try to take another look.</p>","post_number":6,"post_type":1,"posts_count":14,"updated_at":"2024-02-05T15:11:00.274Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":5,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":9,"reads":72,"readers_count":71,"score":64.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":453000,"topic_slug":"input-delay-on-swerve-drive-when-adding-other-subsystems","display_username":"Dylan Powers","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":55902,"username":"vickitine","name":"Victoria","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/vickitine/{size}/180654_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":42126,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/input-delay-on-swerve-drive-when-adding-other-subsystems/453000/6","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3302298,"name":"Victoria","username":"vickitine","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/vickitine/{size}/180654_2.png","created_at":"2024-02-05T18:38:46.936Z","cooked":"<p>I think that will fix it, I’ll try that out.  One thing that we did was move the radio into a place in which it’s not trapped, which helped a lot. Now it’s just some optimization that we need to do. The issue is, I have no idea where else to put the master and follower motor stuff. I know it’s the placement of the followerMotor.setControl(new Follower(masterMotor.getDeviceID(), true)); line in the angleSubsytem.java and launcherSubsystems.java files that’s causing the delay. They need to be initialized once in the start of the program. There is no delay when we add the IndexerSubsystem.java file as there is no master or follower motors, it’s just one motor.</p>","post_number":7,"post_type":1,"posts_count":14,"updated_at":"2024-02-05T18:38:46.936Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":6,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":61,"readers_count":60,"score":22.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":453000,"topic_slug":"input-delay-on-swerve-drive-when-adding-other-subsystems","display_username":"Victoria","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":42126,"username":"Dylan1259","name":"Dylan Powers","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/dylan1259/{size}/161876_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":55902,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/input-delay-on-swerve-drive-when-adding-other-subsystems/453000/7","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3302315,"name":"Dylan Powers","username":"Dylan1259","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/dylan1259/{size}/161876_2.png","created_at":"2024-02-05T18:55:25.033Z","cooked":"<p>You should be able to put initialization stuff in the constructor of your subsystem.</p>
<pre><code>public AngleSubsystem(TalonFX masterMotor, TalonFX followerMotor) {
    this.masterMotor = masterMotor;
    this.followerMotor = followerMotor;

    // motors going opposite directions, change to false if they need to go the same direction for any reason
    followerMotor.setControl(new Follower(masterMotor.getDeviceID(), true));
    // set the mode to brake. make motor hard stop
    masterMotor.setNeutralMode(NeutralModeValue.Brake);
    followerMotor.setNeutralMode(NeutralModeValue.Brake);
}
</code></pre>
<p>In 99% of cases it will work as intended. If there is weird stuff happening you might need to put some delay in the constructor cause EVERYTHING, including the roboRIO and various vender libraries are starting upon the robot getting power, but it should work just fine for basic stuff like that.</p>","post_number":8,"post_type":1,"posts_count":14,"updated_at":"2024-02-05T18:55:25.033Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":7,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":5,"reads":60,"readers_count":59,"score":42.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":453000,"topic_slug":"input-delay-on-swerve-drive-when-adding-other-subsystems","display_username":"Dylan Powers","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":55902,"username":"vickitine","name":"Victoria","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/vickitine/{size}/180654_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":42126,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/input-delay-on-swerve-drive-when-adding-other-subsystems/453000/8","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3303150,"name":"Victoria","username":"vickitine","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/vickitine/{size}/180654_2.png","created_at":"2024-02-06T16:56:52.980Z","cooked":"<p>I tried that out but it completely broke our subsystems. What’s happening now is that the motors stutter and move periodically. I tried putting only the NeutralModeValue in the constructor, only putting in followerMotor.setControl, and putting in both. All of them give the weird stuttering issue. I’ve tried taking out NeutralMode completely and just using the base state of the motor, but then the motors don’t spin at all.</p>","post_number":9,"post_type":1,"posts_count":14,"updated_at":"2024-02-06T16:56:52.980Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":8,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":3,"reads":56,"readers_count":55,"score":31.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":453000,"topic_slug":"input-delay-on-swerve-drive-when-adding-other-subsystems","display_username":"Victoria","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":42126,"username":"Dylan1259","name":"Dylan Powers","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/dylan1259/{size}/161876_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":55902,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/input-delay-on-swerve-drive-when-adding-other-subsystems/453000/9","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3303279,"name":"Dylan Powers","username":"Dylan1259","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/dylan1259/{size}/161876_2.png","created_at":"2024-02-06T18:24:40.352Z","cooked":"<p>Well, that is certainly strange. I haven’t worked much with Pheonix 6 or their Swerve builder so I don’t 100% know where to go from here.</p>
<p>Last year, we ran into an issue with our swerve not resetting the angle motors properly. It came down to the fact that the roboRIO booted faster and started the robot code before the Phoenix Server could fully start. This meant that the statement that reset the angle motor to the proper angle was sent before the Phoenix Server was ready to receive it. We discovered this by putting the module angle reset on a button and it worked after that. The official solution that WPILib and <span class="abbreviation">CTRE<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Cross The Road Electronics"></template></span> devs came up with was a delay before resetting the motors in order to let the Pheonix Server startup.</p>
<pre><code>    /* By pausing init for a second before setting module offsets, we avoid a bug with inverting motors.
     * See https://github.com/Team364/BaseFalconSwerve/issues/8 for more info.
     */
    Timer.delay(1.0);
    resetModulesToAbsolute();
</code></pre>
<p>You could try a delay or putting your configuration statements in a method called by <code>teleopInit()</code> or a button press to try this.</p>
<p>Honestly grasping at straws here.</p>","post_number":10,"post_type":1,"posts_count":14,"updated_at":"2024-02-06T18:24:40.352Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":9,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":4,"reads":55,"readers_count":54,"score":31.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":453000,"topic_slug":"input-delay-on-swerve-drive-when-adding-other-subsystems","display_username":"Dylan Powers","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":55902,"username":"vickitine","name":"Victoria","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/vickitine/{size}/180654_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":42126,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/input-delay-on-swerve-drive-when-adding-other-subsystems/453000/10","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3303300,"name":"Sean B","username":"Phlogiston","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/phlogiston/{size}/180763_2.png","created_at":"2024-02-06T18:48:24.621Z","cooked":"<p>Couple things here. First of all, 0.5s is extremely slow, &gt;25x slower than it should be running. If your software runs slow, it won’t be calling the motor setControl function enough, and motor safety will disable the motors until the next loop, which will cause your stuttering issue. Not sure how configuring the motors every loop is avoiding that, but it is going to slow things down even more, so I’d keep them in the constructor. The issue in both cases is execution speed. Why it’s running so slow could be a lot of factors, I don’t see anything obviously wrong aside from configuring things every loop, so once that’s fixed I’d make sure you don’t have a physical <span class="abbreviation">CAN<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Controller Area Network"></template></span> issue - look into <span class="abbreviation">CAN<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Controller Area Network"></template></span> usage and whether your dropping any packets. Also, I’d go into phoenix tuner and update<br>
your devices + reset configs to factory to rule out the possibility of having something weird in terms of firmware/configuration.</p>","post_number":11,"post_type":1,"posts_count":14,"updated_at":"2024-02-06T18:52:43.129Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":6,"reads":45,"readers_count":44,"score":39.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":453000,"topic_slug":"input-delay-on-swerve-drive-when-adding-other-subsystems","display_username":"Sean B","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":44845,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Lone Coder"},"post_url":"/t/input-delay-on-swerve-drive-when-adding-other-subsystems/453000/11","custom_user_title":"Lone Coder","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3303488,"name":"Victoria","username":"vickitine","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/vickitine/{size}/180654_2.png","created_at":"2024-02-06T21:22:19.153Z","cooked":"<p>So I fixed the issue. Inside each command file we had a variable called “finished” that would return false when the command is finished. We just took that out and just returned false and everything worked. We added the variable to fix another issue, but it seemed to cause more issues :(.</p>","post_number":12,"post_type":1,"posts_count":14,"updated_at":"2024-02-06T21:22:19.153Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":4,"reads":36,"readers_count":35,"score":32.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":453000,"topic_slug":"input-delay-on-swerve-drive-when-adding-other-subsystems","display_username":"Victoria","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":55902,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/input-delay-on-swerve-drive-when-adding-other-subsystems/453000/12","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[{"id":"+1","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":1,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":true,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3307110,"name":"Dylan Powers","username":"Dylan1259","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/dylan1259/{size}/161876_2.png","created_at":"2024-02-11T18:22:53.976Z","cooked":"<p>Looking at your changes, it appears that <code>finished</code> was being set to true in the <code>execute()</code> loop which meant that the command only got one loop before being canceled. However, you were setting those commands as default commands which meant that on the next loop, they were getting rescheduled. My guess is there there is significant overhead from <code>CommandScheduler</code> in cancellling and scheduling commands. Doing that three times per main robot loop was probably causing your delays. Not sure how we didn’t catch that earlier but glad you got it solved.</p>","post_number":13,"post_type":1,"posts_count":14,"updated_at":"2024-02-11T18:22